When $q \approx 0$,
$$
\begin{aligned}
F\left(q^{2}\right) & =\int \rho(r) e^{i \mathbf{q} \cdot \mathbf{r} / \hbar} d^{3} \mathbf{r} 
& \approx \int \rho(r)\left[1+i \mathbf{q} \cdot \mathbf{r} / \hbar-\frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{q} \cdot \mathbf{r})^{2} / \hbar^{2}\right] d^{3} \mathbf{r} 
& =\int \rho(r) d^{3} \mathbf{r}-\frac{1}{2} \int\left(\rho(r) q^{2} r^{2} \cos ^{2} \theta / \hbar^{2}\right) \cdot r^{2} \sin \theta d r d \theta d \varphi 
& =F(0)-\frac{2 \pi}{3} \frac{q^{2}}{\hbar^{2}} \int r^{4} \rho(r) d r
\end{aligned}
$$i.e.,
$$
F\left(q^{2}\right)-F(0)=-\frac{2 \pi}{3} \frac{q^{2}}{\hbar^{2}} \int r^{4} \rho(r) d r
$$

Note that $\frac{i}{\hbar} \int \rho(r) \mathbf{q} \cdot \mathbf{r} d^{3} \mathbf{r}=0$ as $\int_{0}^{\pi} \cos \theta \sin \theta d \theta=0$. The mean-square radius $\left\langle r^{2}\right\rangle$ is by definition
$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\langle r^{2}\right\rangle & =\int d^{3} \mathbf{r} \rho(r) r^{2}=4 \pi \int \rho(r) r^{4} d r 
& =-6 \hbar^{2} \frac{F\left(q^{2}\right)-F(0)}{q^{2}}=-6 \hbar^{2}\left(\frac{\partial F}{\partial q^{2}}\right)_{q^{2}=0}
\end{aligned}
$$

From Fig. 2.3,
$$
-\hbar^{2}\left(\frac{\partial F}{\partial q^{2}}\right)_{q^{2}=0} \approx-\frac{0.8-1.0}{2-0} \times 10^{-26}=0.1 \times 10^{-26} \mathrm{~cm}^{2}
$$

Hence $\left\langle r^{2}\right\rangle=0.6 \times 10^{-26} \mathrm{~cm}^{2}$, or $\sqrt{\left\langle r^{2}\right\rangle}=0.77 \times 10^{-13} \mathrm{~cm}$, i.e., the root-mean-square proton radius is 0.77 fm .

